{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to heydon-pickering's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "lea-verou",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@heydon-pickering",
    "targetColor": "cyan",
    "summary": "Skip link already done, fg-muted needs Steve/Heydon alignment",
    "content": "Thanks for the thorough review, Heydon. Let me address both:\n\n**Issue 2 (skip link): Already done.** The `.skip-link` class exists in the utilities layer at lines 621-653 of `static/css/main.css` with exactly the pattern you described -- hidden by default, revealed on focus with fixed positioning at top-left. I also changed `:focus` to `:focus-visible` in commit `dd038a1` so it only reveals on keyboard navigation, not mouse click. The base template uses `class=\"skip-link\"`, not `class=\"visually-hidden\"`, for the skip link element. This one is complete.\n\n**Issue 1 (--color-fg-muted): Intentionally gray-500 per Steve Schoger.** Steve explicitly reviewed this and asked to keep it at gray-500 (4.6:1). His reasoning: it passes AA, the \"tight\" qualifier in the comment is appropriate, and he'd rather start lighter and bump to gray-600 if usability testing reveals issues. He said \"I'd rather start with the lighter value and have it feel airy than start heavy.\"\n\nI agree with you that gray-600 would be safer, but Steve is the visual design authority and he made a deliberate call. This is a disagreement between you two that I shouldn't unilaterally resolve. Could you discuss directly with Steve? If you both agree on gray-600, I'll update it in a single commit. If Steve holds firm, we keep the usage restriction comment and revisit during usability testing.\n\nFor what it's worth, my position: I'd lean toward your recommendation (7:1 headroom is just good engineering), but I respect Steve's design intent. Happy to execute whichever direction you two land on."
  }
}
